segments.text: This is June 19th.
I'm in the office of Paul Geisel at the University of Texas at Arlington.
Paul is a full professor in the Urban and Regional Planning Program.
Paul, first of all, when did you come to UT Arlington?
I came here in 1970.
When was that, Paul?
Uh-huh.
Where were you before?
I was at Arizona State.
In planning?
No.
No, I was in the Department of Sociology there.
And before that, I was the director of the War on Poverty in Canada.
In Canada?
Uh-huh.
Out of which...
In Ottawa.
Ottawa.
Uh-huh.
So I was a deputy minister there.
I see.
Are you Canadian?
No, I'm not.
I had come there.
I was a chairperson of one of the Kennedy task forces on health services for the poverty program.
And after Kennedy's assassination, one of the Canadians asked me if I would like to lead that program there, so I went there from the University of Pittsburgh.
I see.
So you have a degree in sociology from Pittsburgh.
I have a degree in, yes, no, I have a degree in sociology from Vanderbilt.
Vanderbilt.
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
And a degree in mathematics from Chicago, and a medical degree from Chicago.
That's quite a background.
Yeah, well, I was a child when I graduated from college, so I couldn't get a job.
You wouldn't want to know why I'm so educated.
It's because I couldn't get employed.
I got out of college when I was 16, so it's great to be a prodigy, but what the hell are you going to do with it?
And now, in terms of the department here, what... You mean how do I get into this department?
Yeah, what is your role in the department?
Okay, I'm in the department for essentially two reasons.
One...
In the evolution of the urban affairs program here at UTA, it became clear to us that a planning degree of sorts was a necessary and important ingredient.
So in 1972 or 73, I can't remember the exact dates.
It could have been 74.
actually came to fruition in 75.

We started a process with the School of Architecture and several other departments of writing proposals, and I was the author with a fellow, Peter Stewart, over in architecture, of the original proposal for the MCRP at UTA.
Now, that was in concert with a series of other degrees, and because of the kind of work I was doing as a sociologist, as a demographer in particular, it's kind of my area in mathematical sociology,
and the kind of experience I was having working in smaller cities, I was doing a lot of planning, if you will, particularly in terms of social planning and population analysis.
Well, it was a natural evolution.
I'd also started writing
planning manuals for small cities and how to train planning commissions.
And we were doing a lot of that here.
I had developed this emphasis in the small city areas and was very interested in seeing that they could develop a planning process.
So my interest in the area, as well as the university responsibility of having an author, and an author with rank to the proposal,
to carry the proposal.
So the original idea then was to put it in architecture as a home.
There's nothing unique about that.
I didn't particularly care for it.
I didn't think it was essentially appropriate at that time.
But there was no place else to put it.
That's when Hal Box was here.
Yes.
And Hal's an old friend, and looked like we had a pretty trustful relationship.

It also looked, in the university setting at that time, as everyone knows in Texas, that whatever arrangement you made, we were also raw and knew that it really wasn't going to make much difference, that traditional academic games and the theocracies of the disciplines weren't going to be terribly painful here.
Well, clearly we've matured, and clearly that was wrong.
So, you know.
They are painful, eh?
Well, they are, and obviously they're
You know, this university is just like all the rest of them.
Maturity is a pain in the patuggies in terms of trying to be innovative, creative, and do some things a little differently, or at least be contemporary.
So applied and professional programs will always struggle on any university campus.
It's kind of a given that there will always be a little bit of indignity associated with it.
Now, with planning, they're never sure.
It has a certain ring of dignity about it that indicates there must be some theory there.
And if they ever found out there wasn't, we'd all die.
But at this point, at least, we can go through the illusion.
It's good to have a course in your curriculum called planning theory.
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
And then not acknowledge what it was at all.
So just went through one, by the way, though, as I said.
major kind of a question of theoretical perspective that you find.
I've just returned.
I've taken a class to Peru, and I've been taking classes abroad here recently.
And without even thinking about it, our strategies theoretically for the resolution of almost everything now in housing, transportation, political process, you name it, is mainstreaming.
is that you shouldn't build separate discrete units or try to organize utopias or new neighborhoods or anything of the sort.
You really ought to integrate into the city and let the dynamics of the natural market flow kind of operate on it.
And that way, people will integrate into the society.
And the society is a self-healing phenomenon.
That's our new theory out there, if you want a bottom line trash.
How does, uh...
I don't know how all that came about.
We just bought into that one.
But, you know, when you go abroad, they haven't bought it.
Uh-huh.
Well, does a person like Mel Weber and his philosophy of systems approach... Well, all of them, everybody confirms it now.
But no one acknowledges that it's universal and that we just slipped into this one day.
Obviously, you can defend it now that we've done it.
I mean, clearly it's the right thing to do.
But I haven't seen a single article that debates whether this is something we have to do in absolutely everything.
This notion of the healing society out there, the race, see, here come our people.
Anthony Downs says, well, if you dismiss black people out there in suburbia, the race issue will go away.
Well, thank you, Anthony.
I don't have to buy into that one.
You got deaf kids?
Well, the problem is they find out if they study only with deaf people, they find out they're deaf.
So it's better to keep them in public school with all the rest of them, see?
So it's universal.
Housing, well, you shouldn't have public housing anymore, or you shouldn't build separate.
You should build on the street the same.
Hey!
And then let the market factors...
So it's the same...
It's the melting pot taken to the absurd extreme.
Oh, as a matter of fact, no, it's the manipulated melting pot.
And that the melting pot will, in effect, be a positive resolution, or at least a resolution appropriate to the political social realities of our world.
That doesn't mean it's going to be a solution, however.
Well, I don't know.
But it hits you in the face that when you go abroad, we just had a meeting with Belunde here, who's an architect planner, and he's built 175,000 units of housing in the last four years.
Doing fine.
In this dirt, he's building.
Where is he building?
In Peru.
One of the poorest countries in South America.
Oh, yes and no.
It all depends on which economy you wish to measure.
The informal economy is doing bad.
Something's going on.
But one of the neighborhoods that we went to see is called Lima Tambo.
He took us there.
And here's a neighborhood that they've built.
Visually, you can see it.
It would be very helpful as planning educators for us
not to individually, as departments, determine what we think is appropriate.
Now, there's a little bit of that, of course, which is obvious.
We have a local market which dominates it.
Probably you guys at A&M don't have a local market.
But we clearly do with the Nellis-Fort Worth and this broader north central Texas kind of an issue, essentially growth being our critical concern.
Also the small city thing, which I mentioned earlier, I think that's kind of our arena.
But really what would be helpful is to sit down and do a needs determination statewide and decide who does what best.
In terms of skills, I think they're essentially the same for all students.
They really ought to know how to work with micros today.
They ought to know what the database systems are.
Subdivision planning and that kind of trash and planning, I think we've kind of moved beyond.
But they ought to know something about that.
They certainly should know the legal characters and planning administration.
So there are basic theoretical and skill courses.
But then the emphasis areas, I think, are unique.
I think they certainly should know about the history of planning.
Absolutely.
Well, they need to know all the professional stuff that appropriately identifies them with this as a meaningful field.
It would be my goal that every student would turn out a thesis or some kind of a product that would be appropriate for APA
something of that sort.
So they are eligible members of the professional community, you mentioned.
For our M.U.P.
degree, we require a professional paper in the last semester now.
Well, I think that...
It's not a thesis, but it's sort of...
I don't care.
Like, instead, we don't want to call it a thesis, because then we'd have to go through the graduate college.
And we'd have to take attention to the margins.
Well, we're agreeing to all of that.
I don't care from a university perspective where we are.
But in terms of their...
Whether they give a full paper or whatever, they ought to, in my mind, be at APA for a professional reason, as a panelist, as a paper presenter.
And they ought to have written something that was submittable to it, whether they go or not.
That's another choice.
So those things, I think, are common to all the departments.
You mentioned one thing, that you thought it would be good for the planning schools to confer and make a decision about which one would be teaching which subject.

Well, here's where I... No, I think there are emphasis areas of specialties that, by all of us covering every waterfront, economic, development, political, you know, etc., none of us are doing very well, if you want my candid opinion in terms of the challenges in Texas.
For example, the whole area of economic development now, which is a major issue in city after city, we're finding they're hiring people from out of state or from other kinds of divisions.
That disappoints me.
We should have anticipated that ourselves as a profession and grabbed it.
Would you call, then, for a conference of planning faculty and directors?
If we could do that without this one-upmanship,
And I really feel like we're kind of beyond that.
I don't know why I find it unpleasant to deal with the Austin people periodically, but they do have an attitude problem.
And they kind of need to get rid of it.
Well, they're not the only school that has people who have very definite ideas.
Oh, I don't care about that.
I can deal with that.
Because some of them also have such non-voyant personalities that you can just ignore them or whatever and say, fine, that's just fine, you turkey.
And frankly, you know, A&M has a number of those as well.
Those are some of our flamboyant characters, and I don't give a crap about that.
If that means that you have the skill to uniquely offer something better than I, we're all going to cover everything.
Give me a break.
But if you wanted a special, if your goal was to be a small city planner, for example,
I think we offer the best access for it.
Now, if your idea is statewide or regional planning, we're just in on that one.
Don't put that on the tape.
Erase that from the tape.
It's on the tape.
But you understand.
We have a course in regional planning.
I don't even think we describe or identify what a region clearly is.
And A&M, I think, is strong on planning law and land development and transportation.
All right.
We're fair in transportation.
And history.
We're very big in history.
Those are not, we cover them.
But if we came down there, then we could see what we were missing and we could probably recruit to the state.
And we could, you see, one of the advocacies also that's necessary, you know this as well as I,
I have to stop through city halls in this region continually to look at their work job descriptions and discover that these degrees disappear as a part of the description with regularity.
Good point.
We try to assume that we're in a very stable employment market.
Well, forget it.
They feel that if you're not exclusively in the Department of City Planning doing subdivision review or something trivial of that sort, you're not.
It's not a planner.
The fact that you might go into the Department of Transportation, the Department of Water, Sewer, Public Works even, in terms of the planning components, we fight that war every day.
Good.
That's great.
Now, I do it by simply walking through the city hall and calling for the job descriptions, and I find the degree in planning slips out of there very quickly.
The second thing is the advocacy of what is a planner.
It used to be an ugly word.
We all know that.
I mean, for Christ's sake.
Well, it's kind of legit now.
You think it is?
Oh, yeah.
Planning has come back into its own?
Oh, yeah, but the neighborhood movements and things like that in Dallas and Fort Worth and here, we're clean because the planners are citizen advocates.

I mean, see, we went through that wave, and so the people we have placed out there, because of that wave of the intellectual movement, you know, when everything was citizenship, well, those are our senior planners in this region now as our graduates.
So we have
dignity, because we have this citizen political force hitting the fan at the same time.
Now, any of them write, well, I don't care.
We're just very popular.
Now, is there any money?
Well, forget it.
But are we doing good?
Hey, we're hot.
Well, that's interesting because I hadn't been aware of this sort of swing back to popularity.
Well, with the folks.
I can remember back in 1953 when I entered planning, planners could do no wrong.
Oh, they were gods.
Well, we had a mystique surrounding us.
Oh, yeah.
And no one even dared question that mystique.
Listen, I worked with Cal Hamilton for years.
Oh, did you?
Oh, yeah.
In Los Angeles?
No, I worked with him in Pittsburgh before he got fired there.
Uh-huh.
Oh, it was wonderful.
As a matter of fact, my prior book,
I had a million dollar grant from Cal.
Do you like that one?
To simulate the city.
Holy banana.
Because we had that arrogance in those days.
That was 64, 65.
Yeah, we did have a lot of arrogance.
Yeah, and well, you want to know what else?
I believed it was possible.
Well, you probably know all about Brett Harris, though.
Oh, yeah.
And his dog and pony show.
about regional science, he would drag around the country.
Well, we all were.
All of us were stomping around America, and of course the reality is we were probably right, but we were way ahead of our methodological skills to make it all possible.
It really was a nonsense period, but it was fun.
Oh, yeah.
And trashy comedy at the same time is, I believed it was feasible.
I mean, I could laugh over the absurdity of these things today.
They really weren't absurd.
They were feasible, but no one wished to really acknowledge that the databases were the pits.
They were built upon information that no more predicted a kind of a logic.
It was built on so many assumptions.
My best model was Tom.
You had the name Tom.
The time-oriented metropolitan model.
Well.
Have you heard of PLUM?
Oh, no, what's PLUM?
PLUM is Projective Land Use Model.
Oh, I like that.
Well, I had PUMP as well, the Phoenix Urban Minorities Program.
Ah, yes.
We were still priming it when I left.
Yes.
Well, anyway.
My biggest study, by the way, was Nipple.
The National Inventory of Poor People's Lives and Evaluation.
And the government had a conniption fit over that, so we changed it to CUPS.
Canadian Urban Poverty Study.
And they didn't like that, so we went to UPS.
And they kept telling me, you're really obscene.
So we ended with New Life.
New Life.
The National Low Income Family Evaluation.
Then I found out that was a program in Vietnam, so it just
I was ruined.
Just ruined.
Must have been frustrating.
Well, if you name these studies, you can get anything.
Tom really was a good grid model.
I legally am, but actually I don't participate that much in terms of the planning for the department because my degree isn't in planning.
My primary appointment isn't in that department.
What is your primary appointment?
Oh, it's in urban affairs.
Would you explain to me the difference between... Urban affairs and urban planning?
Yeah, are they both departments or are they...
They were.
At this point, we all seem to be one glorious faculty.
How many are there?
How many faculty?
Do you know how many students you normally enroll in the programs?
I know for urban affairs, I can't tell you for planning.
I don't know how many there are close to it.
I think there are about 50, 55 in planning.
We have in the MA in urban affairs, 58.
And in the PhD program, about 60 at this time.
Uh-huh.

Then for those who come in for what we give corollary degrees, we give an MA in MSW, an MA in Urban Journalism, which we kind of are running but has not been completely approved by the Coordinating Board, and then MA with Urban Education.
So those constitute another about 20 students, then the interdisciplinary students that come.
I see.
So we only have graduate students here in this entire faculty.
There are no undergraduate courses whatsoever.
You don't have any service courses for undergraduates?
Not a one.
Now, we did for a while.
And we've tried that angle principally as a kind of a feeder mechanism to encourage students to major.
That simply didn't work.
Now, we also give city planning courses here in the College of Engineering.
They're not really competitive.
They are engineering courses to a large extent.
And it hasn't really been a very big issue.
But my role with the planners here has been, even as a member of that faculty, not to go to their meetings unless they just needed my insight.
You go to the Sociology Institute meetings?

yes if i go to any and i go to urban affairs association which is a small group and i go to apa and i go to the american population association that's kind of you know it's enough is enough yeah you can get drowned oh yeah believe me apa is enough oh and of course i go to that one out of kind of fascination i've usually gone because i was getting a paper or presentation and have been active
periodically with the local chapter.
Our students kind of dominate it.
It's a big chapter.
The northern section.
Uh-huh, sure.
And so I have periodically been active, but in the last two or three years, really not.
What is your perspective on what they're doing in Austin with their planning program?
Do you have any facts to hold on that?
The thing is that
Most of my concerns, I think, really were registered in the first part of this conversation.
I wish someone would sit down and realize what the state's needs really were, and could help us establish a research and placement agenda.
I've never really known what they teach.
Well, that's where I am.
I always feel like we're contemplating the theories of Mao.
from that going into a kind of a philosophical way.
And you say, who's going to hire these turkeys?
We're in a staging in Texas of trying to bring urban spaces along, trying to give them an essential concept that you can get control of ordinances.
You can get control of streets.
You can get control of water, et cetera.
And it'll pay you to do it.
Now, we're just at that still initial stage.

My analysis of manpower needs, which I did about four years ago for planners as a part of a larger study, was that if we could show them what they need, we have about 4,000 positions open in this state that meet those kinds of demands.
But we haven't examined how to fit that, how to match it.
Also, we haven't really told our students where these jobs are or how to get them.
We've had good liaison with the Texas cities.
We've had no difficulty with our planning departments.
I don't mean the League of Texas cities.
Yes, sure.
But this has only been on legislative matters.
Sure.
The state legislature has not been with their local units, their memberships.
And maybe it should work the other way.
We should be working with the league in terms of disseminating the need for getting planning degrees as part of the job description.
Even for, say, consultants.
Yes, consultants.
In this area, consulting firms constitute almost 50% of the employment for planners.
And of course, anyone can put planning in their title.
Thank you very much.
And we should be preparing specially for that.
One of my students works for Segal Associates, which is a national real estate developer, evaluator, planner.
Segal?
Segal.
They do the Segal newsletters.
Oh, not Ladislav Segal.
No.
No.
Nothing that noble or ennobling.
And so...
But that kind of research in real estate research, for example, which is appropriate for our kinds of students, we really haven't tackled that market.
And we're in a data shortage right now, which is unreal.
What ever happened to the 1985 census?
What ever happened to the 1985 census?
for example.
Whatever happened to that?
We were going on the five-year cycle, and then we didn't go on the five-year cycle.
Exactly.
And no one ever even mentioned it.
Now, we did in the American Population Association.
Did you?
Oh, yeah.
What was the answer?
Mr. Reagan was elected.
Oh.
Pardon me, I've got dry eyes.
That explains a lot of things.
Yeah, that's what happened.
That was very simple.
We lost the Biden.
And the question mark was, did we spend the money then for a bad census?
which was only going to give us total count, and possibly raise, or, which wasn't very hot, because you weren't going to get an age break out, and what were you going to be able to do with it?
So, or would you save the money, hide it, realizing that the same budget's coming up for the 1990 census that was there for 1980?
You got the picture now?
So we took the 85 money and hid it.
I won't ask any more questions.
Well, that's where it is.
Demography Magazine discussed this in the last issue.
Is this enough for you?
Because I need to take this.
